<item>
            <title>[LU-3463] Create mock-based build farm capability</title>
                <link>https://jira.whamcloud.com/browse/LU-3463</link>
                <project id="10000" key="LU">Lustre</project>
                    <description>&lt;p&gt;To support proper build procedures for rpm-based distributions, we need a build farm that is capable of building rpms the way that a distro like Fedora does it: using &lt;a href=&quot;http://fedoraproject.org/wiki/Projects/Mock&quot; class=&quot;external-link&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot; rel=&quot;nofollow noopener&quot;&gt;mock&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Each piece of software that we want to build should have a .src.rpm.  That .src.rpm should have all proper dependencies expressed to allow it to be built under mock.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;We&apos;ll need something that sits on top of mock to coordinate the build of dependant packages.  At LLNL we use a home-grown script, that honestly has probably exceeded its lifetime.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;I would suggest that we again evaluate &lt;a href=&quot;http://fedoraproject.org/wiki/Koji&quot; class=&quot;external-link&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot; rel=&quot;nofollow noopener&quot;&gt;Koji&lt;/a&gt;, which is Fedora&apos;s solution.  I haven&apos;t used it personally, so I don&apos;t know how suitable Koji would be.&lt;/p&gt;</description>
